    "body": "@alexcrichton Sorry, I made an incorrect comment about number of quotes and it was misleading to mention to Bash there.  POSIX sh supports [single-quote strings which don't accept any escaped characters](http://pubs.opengroup.org/onlinepubs/9699919799/utilities/V3_chap02.html#tag_18_02_02).  But when we write two or more strings without any intervening word delimiters (`$IFS`,) they are internally concatenated.  OTOH `\\'` is one of the standard escaped characters outside a single-quote string.  So `'a'\\''b'` denotes a single string of three letters and we may colloquially say we escape a single quote as `'\\''` in a single-quote string.\n\nI'd like to support this patch.  I would say, if\n\n> `Show` is intended for debugging\n\nthen it **does need**\n\n> to be a 100% accurate representation of the underlying primitive\n\nbecause we don't want to do debugging based on inaccurate information.  Also, this approach makes reverse conversion simpler.\n\nPassing parameters to a child with 100 % correctness is quite tricky on Windows and it does **not** mean \"we can copy&paste the final parameter string to `cmd.exe`:\"\n- http://blogs.msdn.com/b/twistylittlepassagesallalike/archive/2011/04/23/everyone-quotes-arguments-the-wrong-way.aspx Jump to \"Conclusion\"\n\nThat is, there are cases we need to choose from two different alternatives:\n1. a raw string passed to Win32 API `CreateProcessW()`, or\n2. a string which we can copy&paste to `cmd.exe`\n",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
